    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Movie Star, Or a President?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ilsa Demby Barber letter argues that something is wrong when our politicians are being judged and rated by their performance as show-business personalities rather than on issues (Gail Collins's Oct 13 column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''El Gore,'' by Gail Collins (column, Oct. 13):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''El Gore,'' by Gail Collins (column, Oct. 13):</p>
        <p>Something is wrong when our politicians are being judged and rated by their performance as show-business personalities rather than on the issues and how they would turn their ideas into fact.</p>
        <p>No one doubts that both Al Gore and George W. Bush want to make this country greater. Does it really matter if Mr. Bush stumbles on his words? Dwight D. Eisenhower could never read a speech without mangling the syntax. Does it matter  that Mr. Gore lacks charisma? He has experience and is an environmentalist, which is important to me.</p>
        <p>We have started looking for movie-star presidents, and if we continue to do so, we are surely heading for trouble because in the real world there is only one take.</p>
        <p>ILSA DEMBY BARBER  Colonia, N.J., Oct. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
